 centrality of Mexico City's public markets to the political economy of the city from the restoration of the Republic in 1867 to the heyday of the Mexican miracle and the PRI in the 1960s. Each day vendors interacted with customers, suppliers, government officials, and politicians, and the multiple conflicts that arose repeatedly tested the institutional capacity of the state. Through a close reading of the archives and an analysis of vendors' intersecting economic and political lives, Ingrid Bleynat explores the dynamics, as well as the limits, of capitalist development in Mexico.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCapitalismzMexicozMexico CityxHistory. 0aMarketsxGovernment policyzMexicozMexico CityxHistory. 0aMarketszMexicozMexico CityxHistory. 0aVending standsxGovernment policyzMexicozMexico CityxHistory. 0aVending standszMexicozMexico CityxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh  aConfederación Nacional de Organizaciones Populares.  aMexican miracle.  aMexico.  aPartido Revolucionario Institucional.  acapitalism.  adevelopmentalism.  amarket vendors.  aproprietary mode of production.  apublic markets.  aurban politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362830440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503628304423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503628304/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles